The Ukrainian parliament today rejected a proposal to abolish the section of the Criminal Code under which the opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko was convicted.
The amendment, which would have opened the way for the release of the jailed former prime minister, was rejected by MEPs at second reading on a proposal to ease penalties for economic offences.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for allegedly entering into an unfavorable contract with Russia to purchase natural gas.
The verdict is not final, the convict's appeal is due in December.
Tymoshenko calls the verdict a political revenge of the regime, and the trial has sparked suspicions of bias in the West.
The proposal to remove Article 365 of the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 MPs.
