Diet of an obese child: no breakfast and no dinner
More than one third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 are overweight, with 9 percent of schoolchildren being overweight and 5 percent being obese.
Obese children, however, tend to come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, as a recent survey showed.
Once again, the importance of the environment and patterns surrounding one's growth for healthy human development is being demonstrated.
For example, obese children have up to half the incidence of bedbugs on the tables of normal-weight families.
It's no coincidence that fries were eaten at dinner the day before a research-related awareness campaign called Obesity, more than 19 percent of obese people.
And in families of obese children, sports are not the norm, as is the case in most families of schoolchildren today - only 15 percent of the children said that their parents would take time to exercise at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out at the end of last school year and involved almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic.
This was the second year of the Obesity Is Not a Chance campaign, sponsored by the General Health Insurance Corporation and Unilever.
So far, more than 12 000 pupils from 4th to 8th grade have been involved in the project.
Proper diet and exercise in the family are among the factors that are causing the dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children.
"For example, only half of those surveyed reported eating five times a day in the breakfast-snack-lunch-snack-dinner mode, which is one of the basic requirements of proper nutrition", says one survey.
No breakfast and no dinner
Experts point out that relative details, such as regular family breakfast time, are also essential for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of schoolchildren's families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst was finding that one in ten households didn't eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that unhealthy fries are much more common in families with obese children.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweetened soda every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly exercise, less than half - 15 percent - of their parents did.
Make your own menu
The next part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to make their own menus according to their own tastes and opinions from the options offered.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition".
Their favorite foods include many meaty, meaty, and sweet dishes.
"The popularity of sweet sodas is particularly alarming", says the final report of the survey.
Pasta was the main meal, just above the chicken.
But the children were virtually unwilling to eat any peas, and fish and vegetable lunches are not popular.
Health Benefits
The survey also showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if given the right information.
"It is not by chance that the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the Obesity awareness lecture had a significant shift in preference towards healthy eating principles in a number of cases", the project results state.
This was particularly noticeable in the case of sweetened sodas, where more children began to prefer plain water.
Children were also much more likely to check the questionnaire for poultry and fish as the main meal of the day and to limit sweet foods and dumplings.
A stylist must also be a good psychologist, say the professionals
In the opening article on how stylists learn, I complained so much that there was already a lot of that in the opening lesson.
I had no idea what was going to happen next.
Three lectures from industry experts, dressing up problem figures, and a seminar on how to do things on the court.
It's going to get worse.
The closer we get to the final exam, the more information and practical tasks await us.
And even though the course is held every Saturday and Sunday, it's really "trampled on".
