And that's the vast majority of them.
Some have short necks, some have a boyish figure with no curves, and some are overweight.
The stylist must know how to optically smooth the broad shoulders, lengthen the neck, or add the necessary curves.
We got tips on how to make a woman like Jennifer Lopez, with bigger breasts and hips and a narrow waist, look good and not dress too provocatively.
For example, if the gap between the waist and the hips is such that the skirt or pants don't really fit, it's worth having at least one of those pieces made to measure.
You won't regret it, because perfectly fitting clothes are priceless.
You'll feel much better in a custom skirt than one that keeps moving, twisting, pulling back in your waist and so on.
The boy character can afford to wear clothes with embroidery, makeup, or embroidery.
There's a lot of information and characters out there, of course, so I'm glad I have all week to sort through all the information in my head.
And I'm afraid, with all the homework I've been given, it's just too much.
Each student was assigned a celebrity to design two outfits: a daytime outfit and an evening outfit.
We must take into account the current appearance, the fashion style of the personality, and the type of character.
I'm going to be dressing up Miranda Kerr, who you may know from the Victoria's Secret campaigns.
I'm a lot better in spirit, for me personally, than Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera, who has gained maybe 100 pounds recently (please take the hyperbole into account), or the young Selena Gomez.
We have to cut the clothes out of magazines or search the Internet and print them out and then graphically process them.
Moodboard, as the result is called, then expresses our personal style and relationship to graphic representation.
It's important to think about the graphic side of the design.
A stylist not only dresses physically, but also creates, for example, so-called product pages in magazines (for specific tasks, such as trends in handbags, coats, etc.).
That's what the stylist and designer Mario Kameník told us.
