The stylist must have a general overview
The Saturday lecture, loaded with information on character types, was immediately spread by three industry guests.
The stylist is Honza Pokorny, the fashion designer is Jakub Polanka and the fashion photographer is Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and a stylist should be able to use it.
And a good stylist can work with one piece of clothing in different ways.
Variability is key here.
For example, a trenchcoat (or if you want to call it a trenchcoat) can be worn classically over jeans and a shirt as a cape, but you can also wear it on your bare body, bootstraps, and as a dress.
Or you just pull the sleeves or the collars and the whole look is different.
"Play with it", he insisted.
But what I appreciated most was the following advice: "To work, you need to know the rules perfectly".
"Then you can start breaking them", said Jacob.
So I finally understand why we're all so overwhelmed with all these lessons about what to combine with what, what to do with, why, when even in fashion magazines we often see something else.
Not to mention the shows.
Thanks to Ben's photographer, I know that a stylist has to have a lot more options than there are to photograph.
So for a fashion story that's going to be 10 pages, I have to be ready to "fit" at least 15.
And also that the clothes in the photo look and function differently when combined with other pieces of leckda than they actually are.
So we have to think about that when we're designing outfits.
That image and style make up half of success, Honza the Humble confirmed.
You just have to look at Madonna, who's not exactly a miracle singer, but her image and marketing have made her a global star.
In the Czech Republic, the approach to the use of stylists is rather cold.
Even familiar faces sometimes consider it useless (I'm good at something, my looks are secondary).
And if someone is going to let us create a styling, then we should expect that they will very likely dictate a completely different size than they actually have.
Then all you have to do is google and see if the tabloids have written about the celebrity getting fat or losing weight or whatever.
Honza and Mario told us on Sunday that it's not enough for a stylist to know how to dress and how to dress.
In his work, he communicates primarily with the people he wears, so it's important to be a good psychologist, too.
To judge people, not to be judged, to stand by your own opinion.
"If some manager asks you to sort out her closet and fill it with nice pieces, you can't throw her the whole closet out and say, 'Oh, my God, that's horrible.'"
"Find at least a few things you can recommend and wear", says Mario.
He also showed us in detail what a so-called "placebo", or bag, must contain.
It's the one you put around your waist and you have all the properties.
In addition to the obvious things like scissors, hair rollers, or closing pins, there are also silk thread (used by the stylist to help photograph products such as bags or hats), special clips to be used to sew the back of clothing if it is larger (a pin or other clasp is not allowed, it would damage the garment), or stitches.
To not only listen but also to experience something, we learned how to properly glue our shoes.
Even in a studio with a flat surface, the base could be damaged, let alone outdoors.
And so we glued and glued.
We can't even touch the shoes with scissors, so they don't get damaged.
So it takes real skill.
Mario was delighted when he complimented my work without reservation.
That skill is not really my friend.
