I'm starting to realize that styling on a professional level is really not a walk in the park, no matter who says what they want.
In Need for Speed: The Run, they race across America.
The reviews
A careless ride turns into a routine morning shift because of a series of unnecessary lazy mistakes.
The ambition has been largely fulfilled, but it is not valid if nobody is clearly willing to do anything extra.
The new installment, subtitled The Run, was highly anticipated upon release.
He promised to take this year's Need for Speed series in a new direction, and from the playable visuals, it seemed like a game that might not be limited to the action racing genre.
We were also curious about the inserted passages where the main character gets out of the car and runs off.
But as is the custom with the NFS series, many things turn out a little differently than we expected.
They're potentially decent arcade races, but the whole thing is dragging down a few unnecessary bugs that have been appearing in the series for at least a few years now.
So they're not really bugs, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You are introduced to a story in which the protagonist Jack has certain personal problems and the solution is offered by participating in an illegal race across America.
You get behind the wheel of a car on the West Coast in San Francisco and your mission is to get to New York City first.
The idea has several interesting elements.
The course is divided into ten stages, and then more than fifty races.
This means that each race is run on a different track and the stages are set in different, quite different and interesting environments.
You don't get the feeling for a second that the game is always the same.
Some of the environments are also very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics corresponds to previous parts of the series.
So it's not a worldly thing.
But riding through the desert, through the autumn landscape, or high in the snow-capped mountains is visually very pleasant.
And the races are occasionally marred by some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you'll wind up in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be careful not to get hit by an avalanche.
Besides, the individual races are quite well-arranged.
There's only a few types, but that's enough.
For a moment, you are trying to overtake the required number of opponents (basically a classic race), then you catch up (a classic foot fight), and then you are faced with a duel with a single opponent.
The police will also intervene from time to time, further undermining your efforts.
The new thing is the off-road passages.
It's more like an interactive animation where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
Surprisingly, though, there are far fewer of these passages in play than you might expect (perhaps even just three in particular).
But in the end, it's a good thing, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying, and in the context of the above, it's one of the elements that diversifies the game.
The ride model follows in the footsteps of the previous installments.
That means it's definitely not a big deal nowadays, but it's not a negative.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But for the more action-packed racing, the car still fits the bill, although we could have found a better one.
So far, everything is perfectly fine.
But problems start to appear after a while.
Unlike the road model, the crash model is not very good.
We don't expect this type of game to count complex deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how your car will behave before you hit any object, then you're probably not doing it all right.
Typically, in a close-up or in passing cars in normal traffic, you will sometimes only lick each other slightly, but other times in an almost identical situation your car will end up in wild pirouettes.
Or even to attack directly.
The restart system doesn't make it any more difficult, but it'll keep you in a good place.
The restarts are designed so that if you break down or go far off track, the game throws you back to the last rest stop on the track.
But there are only five restarts available in each race.
When you run out of them, you have to start the race all over again.
So it's more of a fallback aid than a reliable one.
Sometimes even a restart won't help, it'll solve them by having to learn a certain section of the race by heart.
The great disadvantage of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns require a specific route, or you simply cannot get into them.
Other times, you will encounter "civilian" vehicles in the same configuration at a given location, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds early or a minute late.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see the two opposing cars passing in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in a position where you have to overtake or brake.
It doesn't matter when you get to them, because it's "calculated" so that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
The opponents have another advantage.
You'll come across several places throughout the game where, again, regardless of the time, you'll always be overtaken by the same opponent at the same place.
It's the most striking at the end of the game on the long bridge, where you're going in opposite directions.
The adversary must get there before you at any cost.
If it's in front of you, it's going to make your view of the other cars worse, so you're going to be a little bit of a mess at first.
The intention is understandable to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-fueled, but the execution is so obvious that it will surely disgust you quickly.
And that's a shame, because even with a simple ride model, it's fun and so action-packed that sometimes you can't quite see where it's going.
And it doesn't really matter whether it's a concept with 50 unique tracks, or a race schedule where boredom doesn't have a chance, or whatever.
The unconventional idea is to switch cars during races.
You have to be careful of the gas stations on the roadside, because that's where you can change the car, even though in the vast majority of cases you'll be satisfied with what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American bullfighters for straight highways, and exotic super sports for technical riding, such as on winding mountain roads.
And along with the main story mode, there's also the challenge mode, which is racing in the locations you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but experience points for your profile, which is shared by challenges and stories.
To get a higher level of driver, different subjects are unlocked: starting with cars and ending with backgrounds for profile.
It is also linked to the online Autolog feature, which among other things compares your scores with other players and provides additional community features.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
Your car will take you into the subway tunnel (buzz) where you will ride the tracks in the dark (buzz).
The speedometer flashes the numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (buzz) and the meter sets in from behind and uncompromisingly knocks you down.
So we're gonna have a debate in the editorial board for the next few days about whether or not anyone really thought about the game or whether the writers really think we're such a big jerk.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in some cases even great.
It freezes, so at some of the most intense moments, the image drops, and in some cases, quite tragically.
But this is especially true in crashes with a large number of participants, where continuous imaging would no longer be of any use to you.
The soundtrack is fine, and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to a wider audience, the soundtrack was created from the "every dog's a different story" category, but it can be assumed that listening to the music will not necessarily make anyone buy the game.
The overall feel of Need for Speed: The Run is so much more disconcerting.
If the game were to avoid making any unnecessary mistakes, then we wouldn't be afraid to say that The Run is the best NFS game in years.
That's how the game works.
The fun is sure to be great, but be prepared for mistakes to be smashed in your eyes by the force of airport headlights.
