Brand story:
IBM's innovator begins its second century
If you were looking for a word that best describes IBM's strategy, the closest word would be "long-term".
IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution to the general public, a company that is seen as very modern, and yet it has been a hundred years since its founding.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by the company's first CEO, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already coined the slogan that many of the world's problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the imprint around which the life of the future giant would unfold (and also the name of the internal magazine that began to be published at IBM as early as 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson's carefully constructed corporate culture.
"For us at IBM, thinking long term means continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained true to its core values, while not being afraid to change everything else around it.
It has allowed us to transform technology, business and society in our first century.
We hope to achieve even more in the next 100 years", noted Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current CEO, on the occasion of the anniversary.
Refined system
Watson in the 1930s approached his employees in a similar way to the entrepreneur Baťa in the Czech Republic - IBM people were among the first American employees to have paid leave, employer insurance plus elegant work uniforms and a sophisticated system for rewarding the best inventors and businessmen.
IBM has a long-term relationship with its customers that is just as sophisticated.
The company was brilliant in the early days in the development of talent - as one of the first companies in the world to eliminate all discrimination, so that they could choose.
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is to replace Palmisan as IBM's CEO next year with a woman, Virginia Rometty.
She's been at IBM for 30 years, still holding the position of head of sales, marketing and strategy.
IBM has been doing what's called a pit in recent years, an online brainstorming, which has resulted in many future strategies and innovations.
No wonder there's a lot of ideas -- almost half a million people work at the company.
Institutions with a good reputation
The firm's strong internal and external image ensures its position in the business.
"From the beginning, IBM has had the concept of an institution rather than just a technology company", Harvard Business School professor and IBM author Rosabeth Moss Kanter told The Economist.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems by using technology", added George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company says, there's a difference between entering the market and creating the market.
IBM, or "Big Blue", as it is known in the United States for its logo, has grown into one of the world's largest companies in a century.
It is probably the most versatile technology company, developing hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in a range of products from servers to nanotechnology.
It holds the most patents of any American technology company, and five of its employees have won Nobel Prizes.
Her inventions include the ATM, the credit card, the cash swap, the barcode, and the floppy disk.
IBM, with about $220 billion, became the second-largest tech company by market capitalization this year (first behind Apple), surpassing Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations were to the taste of customers and the times - IBM did not, for example, bet on its own OS/2, Prodigy online service or IBM PCjr computers.
"If your business is built to move forward, you cannot be emotionally tied to the past", notes Samuel J. Palmisano.
That's why IBM has no problem building their infrastructure on multiple platforms -- and if they don't work, they abandon it.
Unlike competing Microsoft, which is basically running on Windows.
The future technology
Services account for the largest share of IBM's revenue, with software and hardware accounting for about one fifth.
And yet, back in 1990, it was the strongest hardware player, with more than half of the market.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-yield assets, and during that time, it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of promising technologies.
Investment has continued since 2008, when the modern financial crisis first hit the world.
IBM is following the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who also increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, IBM seems to be going through the current crisis unscathed.
IBM's stock price has skyrocketed 120 percent since the beginning of 2008, and the company's net profit is continuously growing.
IBM's corporate motto is to change everything but its values.
So it's to be expected that even if another crisis comes, this resilient giant will handle it.
The history of IBM: From cheese-cutting to space flight
IBM, the International Business Machines, was founded in New York City a hundred years ago, originally under the shorthand name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was not adopted until 1924 - originally it was a brand used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
The basis for later IBM was the merger of four companies, with a history dating back to the 1880s.
They had technologies like the famous "pushers", or clocks that recorded the arrivals and departures of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also served as chairman of the company's board of directors until 1930.
Flint hired the head of a rival firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the IBM founder - Watson's ideas are still built on an unbeatable corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started out manufacturing and selling all kinds of machines for businesses -- from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During Watson's first four years at the helm, the company doubled its sales to $9 million and began a massive expansion into every continent.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after almost 40 years in the chair, he was succeeded by his son, Thomas Watson Jr.
Under his leadership, IBM began work on artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, humans and computers from IBM helped NASA navigate the flight to space -- to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous manned flight to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "coin", which set the computer standard of the day, called the IBM 5150 came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer manufacturing to Lenovo, a Chinese company, and instead bought the consulting arm of PricewaterhouseCoopers, and began to devote itself fully to consulting and high value-added services.
A strategy that's been paying off for the last three years at IBM -- it's called the Smarter Planet concept.
It aims to make smart use of technologies in areas that are not yet planned, for example in transport and urban management.
For the business sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform, which helps merchants manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history in the domestic market.
It established its branch in what was then Czechoslovakia as early as 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM, the Czech Republic also operates a strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and also has a world-class voice recognition research team.
