How fares have developed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state-owned travel agencies were allowed in what was then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time were selling overwhelmingly only trips to the countries of the Socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very limited.
Czech tourists thus traveled on a seaside holiday to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in the Crimea by the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
The clear exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia was subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually even within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but you had to stay overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good acquaintances" at the travel agency.
But it wasn't won.
The so-called currency pledge, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the journey to the West.
By far the most common holiday destination was the Czech lands, which resulted in a large number of huts and cottages that the Czechs built for themselves, a practice that still persists today.
Travel by Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
The enormous paradox, which we no longer realize today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to what is now the most popular country in the world, Croatia, until 1989 because it was part of what was then Yugoslavia.
The abolition of visas to neighbouring Western European countries in the late 1990s triggered a huge wave of short-term visits, particularly to Vienna, Austria, and Germany.
For a long time, Czechoslovaks could not afford to travel to the West, and everyone wanted to see it for a while.
In Paris, for example, the Czechs' camping trips to parks and tents were not worth the cost of a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech travel at this time was to bring their own food, canned food, salami, etc., to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech koruna, which allowed our tourists to buy Western currency freely after many decades.
But our standard of living and with it the average wage were rising, leading to another important moment around 1997.
The increased demand for travel has led to tour operators regularly offering charter flights since 1997, which have made flights incredibly cheaper than in the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantitative discounts.
By the late 1990s, the Czechs had visa-free access to virtually all the developed countries of the world except the United States, which further facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came in 2000, when the first direct charter flight to exotics was made from the Czech Republic, thanks to a significant demand, it was to Thailand.
From this year, direct charters to warm distant countries are flown every year with Czech tourists, this winter they will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
The exotic country is now visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, symbolizing our post-revolutionary evolution, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US abolished visas for Czech tourists, and our country was definitely ranked among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czech Republic also spent more than half of its holidays abroad (50.3%) for the first time in history and spent more than CZK 15 000 per person on a single holiday abroad, including costs at the place of stay.
