Peter Englund's emotionally powerful new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a list of characters that will make your head spin.
One tip for the moment: Carefully tear this page out and make it a bookmark.
You will get to know all the characters in Mr. Englund's novel very well, and this list will serve as a navigation - a beacon - for those moments when you, like the men and women in the story, feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new vice-president of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are discussing here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as "an anti-historical work".
It contains several well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, but it is almost missing ambassadors, energetic journalists, and discussions of tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, explains the author, as it is "a book about what it was like". It is mainly about "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Sorrow" combines the war experiences of 20 or so men and women on both sides of the barricade, from female students and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people are gonna be heroes.
Others will become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go mad, or die.
Their lives are fading like the flames of a candle lit in a church - new ones are being added to the web of destinies while others are dying out.
Mr. Englund's book is different from the classic historical novels.
It distorts the idea that the First World War was all about the terrible trench warfare on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" also expertly explores other places where war dramas have taken place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book deal with problems like being hit by bee nests, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of pyramids, or dealing with the presence of much tsetse.
Almost from the beginning, it's a very moving read.
War will consume people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
If gunfire starts in the distance and you're a woman at home with your children, will you run or stay?
Who's coming?
Almost no one understands what's going on, even why the whole war was started.
"The vacuum created by the lack of facts", Mr. Englund observed, "was filled with conjecture, conjecture, hope, fear, prejudice, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors".
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are widely adapted from biographies, letters, and other published material.
The accounts of their lives may sound frightening and fascinating, but the incorporation of minute moments and details makes them absolutely vivid and believable.
Many of them are about suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Stuff, everywhere substitutes".
"Coffee cask, imitation aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons. " I was just wondering if you could help me out.
He goes further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "meat made from pressed rice cooked in skimmed fat (and supplemented with a false bone of wood), dried root tobacco and dried potato skins, wooden-soled shoes".
It mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes in sausage making and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American finds an innate drive for savagery and brutality, and then says of war: "Eventually you will understand that this is human nature, not sitting in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, the evening paper or a good book, and pretending that this mask of yours represents civilization, and that behind the starched self inside you there is no barbarian".
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon and no one will even notice, let alone grieve.
