Walls Have Eyes: How Scientists Study You on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man who presented his anti-immigrant views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to the July killing spree that left 77 dead in Norway, attended his first public trial.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was certainly not alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time at his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social networking sites, during the preparations for the attack.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists are eager to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It's easy - just go to Facebook.
"We realized that getting them isn't that hard at all", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by a British research team on European digital populism.
The personal data on Facebook is so vast, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the ads on the page to pinpoint the target demographic with absolute accuracy - something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans across Europe, and they targeted them with ads, but instead of inviting them to join the new group or offering them dietary products, they asked them to fill out a questionnaire asking about their education level, their attitude to violence, and their optimism about their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research", Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: the online followers of right-wing groups are mostly young men, driven by the rising rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more rational, more democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen".
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and policy researchers are using these sites to study everything from health issues to social trends hidden in status updates, wall posts, and "like" buttons.
Facebook has over 800 million active users, each of whom provides three different pieces of data on average every day, making it a social networking "information supernova" that is literally driving a lot of new research, and the number of academic papers with the word Facebook in their names has increased by almost 800% from five years ago.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it allows them to study people without having to harass them on the street.
"It used to be that when you wanted to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You'd have to get to a party where they'd never let you in", says Bartlett.
"Facebook is tearing this down -- you just go right to it".
Others argue that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a social health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren at the University of Wisconsin, a research team found that college students who discussed their drinking experiences on Facebook were much more likely to have a drinking problem than students who kept quiet about the subject.
Moren suggests that peers monitor the site and offer to help a student who posts too many drunk status.
"You can't solve a problem if you can't diagnose it", said Dimitri Christakis, Dr. Moreno's co-author and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington.
"We've found a way to identify at-risk children who we wouldn't have had a chance to discover otherwise".
Facebook itself is constantly probing its users' data.
The site's information team compiled statistics on the relationship status and Valentine's Day relationship, voter turnout in 2010, and the nation's satisfaction ratio (mainly using information they had access to - proponents of Internet freedom have long argued that the site should make its information treasure trove available to research and others).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not - in exchange for the chance to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the page is required to provide their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clear rules about how to collect data offline, but online data is available to everyone.
"I don't think most users even thought that researchers could look at their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using the public Facebook walls of his students.
"If it was them, they took it as information between themselves and their friends".
The question of methodology is also to be considered.
Even in an offline research, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There is no way to verify on Facebook how much of the information on the profile and the posts on the wall are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off of Facebook are two completely different things", Selwyn explains.
That is why Selwin, who has spent many years researching new technologies, believes that pencil and notebook still remain the best research tools.
"When you go out into the real world and talk to real people, it's something that can't be replaced", he says.
"Social research should be about society and social activity -- and hell, a lot of social activity still happens offline".
