As soon as Steve Jobs died on October 5th, opinions began to emerge that compared him to Henry Ford and voted him for his genius as the Greatest Modern Inventor.
In the recently rediscovered interview with Jobs, which was pulverized for a special movie that's heading to theaters this week, it will be a fact for all Apple fans that his creative mind had a perfect understanding of the business processes and workflows behind his products.
A brilliant designer, dreamer, and self-styled hippie, he was also a pedantic organizer and a man who worked every detail - he believed that many entrepreneurs suffered from "the idea that a really great idea is 90 percent of their work . . . [but] there is still a long way to go between a great idea and a great product".
In 1995, Bob Cringely was working on the TV show Triumph of the Computer Madmen, which dealt with the dawn of personal computers, and during the filming, a unique interview took place, lasting over an hour.
By this time, it had been ten years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was busy with his new computer company, NeXT, and he was eager to see the general public embrace the Internet.
The TV show ended up using only a short portion of the entire Cringely interview, and the original copies of the interview were rumored to have been lost in the shipment.
Shortly after Jobs' death, however, VHS copies were found in the director's garage.
This very material, slightly cut, forms the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which is heading to select theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who's famous for his reluctance to give lengthy interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about being able to talk about his technological philosophy and business strategies.
And he also turns out to be a very thoughtful person.
Four times during an interview, there's a longer pause between the question and the answer -- 10 to 15 seconds of thinking, where you can see Jobs thinking through the answer perfectly to make it as accurate and precise as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs's perfectionism comes to the surface, when he seems impatient with Cringely's questions, pushing him to get to more important problems and topics faster.
The interview was filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod, or the iPhone, and it's a terrifyingly prophetic thought as Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing well and badly, while offering his own vision of the future of computer technology.
It's one thing to read the post-mortem reviews of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about Jobs, who we see here as a keen dreamer in the prime of his genius.
He has his own vision of what things could and should look like.
Before long, after he had spoken his thoughts, he began to put them into practice.
A quick summary of seven scenes from the Lost Interview that are definitely worth noting:
How he learned to run the business:
"Over the years of business, I've always asked, 'Why do you do this?' and the answer has always been the same: 'Well, this is just how it's done.'"
No one knows why he does what he does, never thinks deeply about business matters.
I found out.
Jobs goes on to describe his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
He was completely confused by the way costs were recorded - they often started with "standard costs", you could only guess at their amount - and at that point he decided to go his own way - he developed an automated tool that guaranteed that they could determine the business costs in a moment.
How he did the cross-pollination on the pope:
Jobs remembers the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and call anywhere in the world for free.
Much has been written about this device in the past, but Jobs' enthusiasm for describing the Blue Box as an instrument of power is literally contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the device using a pay phone and during the call, they had it be switched from one AT&T network to another while using as many satellites as possible.
"We've been around the world like this at least half a dozen times, so when we shouted something into the pay phone, it would ring a minute later from the other phone at the door", Jobs laughs.
"We were young and we realized that we could build something that could run a billion-dollar infrastructure around the world".
We, the two of us, built a little thing that could control a much bigger giant -- it was an incredible experience, and I don't think Apple would have ever been built without it.
Jobs goes on to describe the joke that he and Wozniak almost got to the end of, where they called the Vatican in the middle of the night via the Blue Box, asking if they could speak to the Pope, making the best of it by impersonating Henry Kissinger.
Gradually, more and more high-ranking members of the Catholic Church were called in to speak with an American diplomat in the middle of the night, and just before the Pope himself was awakened, the couple opened their mouths and hung up.
How he fell in love with technology (and talked to Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 and looking for spare parts to build a meter, he found Bill Hewlett's number in the phone book and called him.
Not long after their 20-minute conversation, Jobs had secured a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had an incredible impact on me. It was the only company I knew at the time, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how it should treat its employees".
Jobs later became one of HP's employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
It was like a suitcase, it had a CRT monitor, and I fell in love with it right away.
As a teenager, I got higher and higher at HP, and I was hanging around this computer and I was writing programs for it.
How they invent innovation:
In several places during the interview, Jobs talks about how he's coming up with new products on the fly.
Early in his career, when he went out to sell some circuit boards, a customer asked him to put together a whole computer for him.
He had only 30 paid days to design, assemble and deliver the finished equipment.
Later, when he was at Apple, he recalls the problems they faced in developing the computer mouse:
"I remember having a pretty wild argument... yelling at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300], when I stopped enjoying it, I went out and found a designer".
90 days later, we were able to make a perfectly reliable mouse for 15 dollars.
How big companies are breathless:
Long before he led the resurrection of Apple, Jobs had predicted that many industry leaders would falter in their vision and lose market share.
"Let's say you work for IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers or printers, so what do you do?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company can't be more successful.
At this point, marketing and sales are the norm, so companies are run by people who are in charge of that, while people who are in charge of their own products are being pushed out of the decision-making process.
The technological genius that has brought the company to its unshakable position is now being replaced by people who have no idea what is good or bad - skill and technical knowledge are essential.
That's exactly what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could own literally the entire computer industry.
It could be ten times bigger than it is, it could be Microsoft of the '90s...
Instead of winning, they lost.
How he sees innovation as an art form:
"There's a long way to go and a lot of work to do between a great idea and a great product... and as the great idea evolves, it changes and grows".
You'll learn a lot about him in that time.
You have to make a whole range of compromises - certain things you just can't make electrons, glass, robots or factories do.
You have to keep 5,000 things in your head all the time -- different concepts -- and put them together...
It's all about taste, in the end, you try to think of the best things that humanity has ever created, and somehow you try to translate them into what you're doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I've never been ashamed of stealing the best ideas.
The reason the Macintosh was so amazing and successful was because the people who worked there were brilliant musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, and coincidentally, the best computer scientists in the world.
Without computers and new technology, they would have done amazing things in completely different industries.
Scalia and Thomas had dinner with health care law opponents while their case was being heard in court
On the day the Supreme Court sat behind closed doors to consider the politically controversial question of whether to accept an objection to President Obama's health care bill, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, attended a celebratory dinner sponsored by a law firm that will attend the trial.
The event occurred last Thursday when all nine judges met to discuss the motions.
One of the cases discussed was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the sweeping health care overhaul passed by Congress last year - a law that mobilized conservative activists around the world.
The judges agreed to hear the case, but a 5.5-hour hearing is expected in March, which will also result in a more thorough presidential election scheduled for 2012 and in full swing by the time the ruling is issued.
The lawyer who will stand before the court and try to get the bill rejected will most likely be Paul Clement, who served as the Attorney General of the United States under George W. Bush.
Clement's law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, which has long advocated for conservative legal principles.
Another company that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the law-challenging trade associations, the National Federation of Independent Business.
The next sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., for which huge amounts of money are at stake in the trial.
The dinner was held at a hotel in Washington, D.C., hours after the court hearing on the case.
Attended by, among others, Mitch McConnell, the top Republican in the Senate and a staunch opponent of the health care bill.
And the introduction of the guests?
It's nothing new: these two judges have been involved in the Federalist Society's activities for years.
And it's definitely not anything that's against ethics.
In fact, these judges are exempt from the obligation to observe the code of conduct to which lower federal judges are subject.
If this were not the case, however, their conduct would certainly fall under principle C4, which states that 'a judge may participate in events organised by related and other organisations for the purpose of raising funds, but the judge may not be a speaker, an honored guest or be included in the programme of the event'.
Yet Scalia and Thomas' relationship to the two law firms involved in the case, as well as the company with a huge financial interest in the case, was enough to alarm activists calling for ethics in government.
"This shocking breach of ethics and disregard for the code of conduct contradicts the assertion of several justices that the Supreme Court follows the same rules as all other federal judges", stated Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"Judges drinking and dining at the benefit with lawyers waiting to hear their case in court".
Their presence and help in raising funds through this event undermines the feet with all the claims of impartiality, which is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little sympathy for their critics, telling them that they too have no problem combining their judicial duties with the actions of groups like the Federalist Society.
Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a high-ranking conservative activist.
The Conservatives also argue that the ethical issue is with Judge Elena Kagan, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was acting attorney general under President Obama when the first objections to the law appeared in court.
Kagan's critics are pressing her to renounce her involvement in the case, saying she fought for the law too hard to be impartial now.
Kagan has made no indication that she intends to resign.
