How to Recognize a Lie
A glance at recent headlines suggests just how serious and pervasive lies and deception are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy accusing several women of sexual harassment - both sides claim the other is lying.
Penn State administrators were charged with perjury after trying to cover up records of a retired football coach sexually assaulting a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught on a microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lies have destroyed careers and stability in many countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately disproved by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of misusing campaign funds to try to conceal his extramarital affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that swept around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual encounter with Monica Lewinsky.
There are stories of cheating in schools and colleges everywhere.
There are instances where teachers themselves give their students test answers just to look good in their own grades.
Mentors who should teach the opposite are sending a message that lying and deception are acceptable.
How many scams are we dealing with?
Studies show you lie anywhere from 10 to 200 times a day.
Suppose many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first ten minutes of their first meeting.
Lies detection, or "lying-recognition", is an essential skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or professional reasons.
But it's not a social game that's like, say, Charades, where you scream, "I got you". Deception detection is a serious branch of science that works with scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities in the course of detailed research projects, especially in psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars are looking you in the eye.
It's not like they're shaking, or whining, or blushing, or sewing.
Of course, do not assume that liars are somehow difficult to spot and detect.
A trained lie detector can detect the truth from sentence structure, tiny facial expressions, the way questions are formed and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from the vast and growing field of lie detection, and it is clear that deception detection is a modern skill that can be easily learned and can be of great help in today's complex world - especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, conducting interviews, negotiating, or managing people.
Good liars read people, let them be alert, direct their emotions, and intuitively perceive how they're perceived.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more "other-centered" lies -- mostly to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than single people do (although the lies they tell tend to be "disgraceful").
We also know that if you're perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's normal behavior.
It's called "initial observation".
It will give him later findings to compare with.
Notice the subject's posture, his laughter, his voice work.
You should know if someone is regularly knocking so that you don't falsely accuse them of lying just because they start knocking in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
But consider these as warning signs, not proof of a lie.
Liars may stop moving their upper body as they try to recall their fabricated story, may turn their shoe to the door, lean out, change their posture dramatically, or display "relief at the end of the conversation" - exaggerated breathing and changing posture when it is difficult to confess behind them.
Interviewers often give a false signal that the interview is over, just to see what relief will be when it is over.
Also, notice the language of the subject.
The story is famous for how Scott Peterson once used his past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which triggered a nationwide search for her body.
Liars may also express themselves in a moderate way, "I had no sexual relations with Mrs. . . . Miss Lewinsky", or repeat the difficult question all the way through.
The most common verbal signs are only very slight.
One can use a lot of "soothing language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... from what I know... to the best of my knowledge".
Such a response does not reveal much of the facts and often provides another warning signal.
There is no magic that can detect every lie, but it is possible to acquire skills that can help you detect a lie.
With these skills, a person will have a better chance of avoiding being a liar and a fraud in his personal and professional life.
