2011 will go down in Sinaloa's economic history as the first year of the government of Maria López Valdez, who calls herself the government of change, which has brought great expectations in terms of economic progress, but due to adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, no growth was recorded and even the main indicators of economic development declined.
The low temperatures in February caused millions of losses in agriculture, limited the growth potential of the state economy, and caused a 3.6% decline in economic activity in the first half of this year, with agriculture experiencing a historic decline of 31.16%, which has also disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to the damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,835 hectares of cultivated land were damaged, of which 78.03% were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% were partially damaged.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a steady increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state recorded an increase during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55,053 residents of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28% and between July and August, the average unemployment rate continued to grow and reached a value of 6.19%, representing approximately 74,000 unemployed.
Less liquidity
According to Gerard López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly by the steps taken at the level of public policy.
"We are seeing rising unemployment, which is related to a variety of factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to resource constraints due to legislation passed by Congress to combat money laundering, and it is not easy for people who illegally take over dollars to make, invest or use them", he said.
Stopping migration
López Cervantes pointed out that the demographic factor also contributes to the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people going abroad to work, to the United States, has been declining, both because of the difficulty of entry and because even when these people get across the border, it's hard for them to find work, so people stay and demand work from our state, and so unemployment is rising", he said.
Unreliability
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is also deteriorating due to the growing uncertainty that prevails in the area of working conditions.
Added to the unemployment and insecurity are other labour market features such as low wages, which are among the lowest in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa State was 5,352 pesos as of September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Reduction of foreign direct investment
Along with declining economic activity and rising unemployment, 2011 also saw the most significant decline in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years. According to the Ministry of Finance, foreign direct investment in the period from January to June amounted to $630,697, representing a decrease of 87.74% from the amount of $5,143,312 in the same period the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government reports investments of P17 280 million per year, mainly in enterprises in the service sector.
The debt
In connection with the downturn scenario, the state government asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy.
Reactions
According to business representatives, the first year of the government of Maria López Valdés showed a lack of governmental management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformative Industries, stated that in 2011 there was a lack of coordination between the will of the individual sectors, including the state government itself.
"The economic development in Sinaloa has been really small this year. We have to work intensively to recover the land that we lost this year. In 2012 we have to double the effort, there was a lack of harmonization of the efforts of all of us and especially the proper and synchronized functioning of this new government. Let's hope that next year will be much better", he said.
Slowdown in the economy
Loredo López said that events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year had halted the state economy and limited its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including the cold. One of the main consequences was the slowdown in the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to regain the momentum needed to achieve acceptable levels of movement of processes, products and services.
Redefining the mission
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Mexican Employers in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed to more dynamic productive activities.
"We think that we need to prepare a long-term plan that redefines the goals and economic direction of the state, because it is important to mobilize all the potential material and human resources that Sinaloa has", he said.
The Work That lies ahead
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of setting a vision for the future that would better guide the government's efforts.
"Generally, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, some progress has been made in economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan", he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in terms of public policy management.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the government is trying to be friendly, I can say that there is work done here and I think the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us", he said.
