"It is almost 12 million, and even though the year is coming to an end, we have received nothing, even though we should have received a portion in July", he said. "To save time, we have started projects and are continuing very successfully, but we lack the money".
He stated that the state had not fulfilled the relevant deliveries during the administration of Jesús Aguilar Padilla last year, and therefore at the beginning of the new period, the city had to apply for a loan to be able to repay more than 7 million that the state administration did not give them.
"The same thing happened to us in the previous six-year period, because the state did not have the economic capacity to participate and the programmes went on.
Despite promises by the State authorities regarding the transfer of these resources, he stated that a request was sent to Armando Villarreal, Secretary for Administration and Finance, to expedite the proceedings and the corresponding percentage arrived as soon as possible.
"We were supposed to get 12 million, and even though the year is coming to an end, we haven't received a single peso yet".
The Court approves 'end of analogue broadcasting' in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme State Court (SCJN) rejected a constitutional lawsuit filed by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against a presidential decree that seeks to expedite the so-called "analogue signal shutdown" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued a decree that outlines the individual steps that will lead to the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the action brought by the Senate was dismissed on the ground that the qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the said decree, which therefore remains in force, had not been reached.
The draft judgment prepared by Minister Olgou Sánchez Cordero proposes the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, since the regulation of all issues relating to radio and television is a matter reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), thus violating the principles of hierarchical subordination and exception to the law.
The only people who voted for the project were Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero herself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported the constitutional dispute in an attempt to fight the decree.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the complaint lodged by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a discussion on the proposal, which is also in the hands of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the proposal in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure measures to prepare public administration through general standards.
"I don't think even if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", he said, recalling that public policy planning in strategic areas like the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has seen in recent years, involving better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
He believes that delaying change would be to delay the benefits of digitalisation, which requires decisions in the public interest, as digitalisation has not only a technical dimension but "also touches on economic, social, political and national security issues".
He stressed that these issues "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic orientation of the state.
He recalled that a number of countries around the world had already completed the digital transition and had done so through their governments, despite having highly specialised technical bodies.
He stated that it was not possible for the government to introduce into the administration the observance of laws prepared by the legislature by issuing a dissenting decree that to some extent interfered with the sphere of powers of Congress.
The Michoacan is analyzing the possibility of a vote-by-vote count.
According to the PREP data, the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is less than 27 percent.
The option of "vote by vote" has emerged in this year's election in Michoacán, where according to the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is less than 27 percent, and 879 of the total 6074 electoral districts have not yet been counted.
In this context, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the Electoral Authority approved a series of measures that should harmonize local standards with the federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán has not officially ratified its political constitution nor its State Electoral Code or Electoral Justice Act, as the state Congress passed the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in this election season and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted their publication by the deadline set in the Official State Gazette Act, citing objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme State Court (SCJN) settled a constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislature, declaring the head of state's vote on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal" because it has no right "neither to approve nor to veto".
When asked about the possibility of a 'vote by vote' count, María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that, with the approval of the relevant measures by the General Council of the IEM, it would be possible for the partial and the total count to be carried out by the local electoral authority.
In this way, a partial count of votes, one or more ballots, will be possible if the following conditions are met: the election results are not consistent; there is no record of the counting of votes and the calculation in the relevant box or it is not available to the chairperson concerned; or if there have been errors and obvious violations of the election results.
In addition, a total recount of votes at all polling stations will be possible where there is evidence to suggest that the difference between the potential winner of the election and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; whenever there is an explicit request at the beginning of the session from the representative of the party and/or coalition that has proposed the candidate in second place.
A total recount of votes will also be possible if, after a proper count, it is found that the difference between the likely winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, and whenever there is an explicit request from the political party whose candidate finished in second place, in which case the ballots for which a partial count has been carried out will be discarded.
It should be mentioned that this is the case in the elections in Morelia, where according to PREP the difference between first and second place is less than 0,16%, even though 129 of the total 923 constituencies have not yet been counted.
His last will and testament
His ashes will be scattered in the Zapalinamé Mountains, his family confirmed.
The remains of the pilot Felipe Bacio Cortés were transported to Saltillo, his hometown, on Sunday night, with a solemn ceremony and a funeral mass to be held on Monday.
According to the family, the lieutenant colonel's last wish was for his ashes to be scattered in the Zapalinamé Mountains.
After being honored along with the other victims of the accident, the Bacio Cortés family returned to the capital of Coahuila aboard a Mexican Air Force plane, where family and close friends attended the ceremony at Campo Marte.
At noon, the lieutenant colonel's ashes arrived at the chapel in the Nazario Ortiz Garza classroom, where family and friends also came.
At 5:30 p.m., a farewell party was held at the Saltillo Institute of Technology, organized by his former high school classmates and members of the American football team, of which Felipe Bacio was also a member during his graduation.
"He wanted to return to Saltilla and his wish was that his ashes be scattered in the Zapalinamé Mountains, as he always told his family and friends", said Sandra Bacio Cortés, the pilot's sister.
She said the lieutenant colonel had fulfilled all his wishes, was at the peak of his life, "was a wonderful man, an extraordinary father, a son, a loving brother who lived for his family".
Felipe Bacio Cortés left the city of Saltillo very young and entered the flying school Colegio del Aire in Zapopán, Jalisco.
Some people didn't believe it because they said he even drove a truck, yet he always went after his dream of becoming a pilot.
His nephew Jorge Alberto Dávila Bacio remembers him as a very good man, "he had barely arrived in Saltillo, the whole family wanted to see him, like when he brought Martha Sahagún to Saltillo".
The young man even recalls that when he was seven years old, he went to Zapopan for his uncle's graduation, so he is convinced that he died doing what he loved most in life: flying an airplane.
They said goodbye to him
With Felipe Bacio Cortés, lieutenant colonel of the Mexican Air Force, we bid farewell to all the honors that have come to him from Governor Jorge Torres López, the citizens and the state government, the Mexican Army through the Sixth Military Zone, the Mexican Air Force itself, the leaders and students of the Saltillo High School of Technology, where he studied in 1985 and where he excelled both in studies and in sports.
Bacio Cortés died in the past few days after the helicopter he was piloting crashed, with the Secretary of State José Francisco Blake Mora on board, and six other people, all officials of this state.
At 6:05 p.m., the remains of Bacio Cortés (incinerated) arrived to be delivered by funeral service to the Mexican Air Force under the command of Major Jaime Martinez, at a plaza where his family, his daughter Amanda and wife Cristina, his mother, siblings and other relatives, students and teachers were gathered.
Three abandoned bodies found on Cadereyta NL estate.
Hours before the discovery, military officials introduced to the media 11 individuals who had been detained in the area for organized crime-related crimes.
The bodies of three men murdered by gunshot to various parts of the body and head were found on an abandoned estate in the municipality of Cadereyta Jiménez, Nuevo León.
The discovery was made on a mile of road from Cadereyta to Santiago, at the level of the area known as El Castillo.
People who moved in these places noticed that the beige-caffeinated hut had its door open from time to time.
When they looked inside from about ten feet away, they noticed three dead bodies, so they immediately alerted the authorities.
One person was wearing a yellow sports shirt and dark cotton pants and was not wearing a baton, and next to him was a man in a white striped sports shirt.
A few yards away was the body of another person dressed in a red sports shirt and blue cotton pants.
All three lay face down.
According to the information obtained at the scene, all three people were probably murdered in a different location, as no bullets were found.
There were messages on the walls of the cabins addressed to one organized crime group and another, as well as a series of bullet marks, both on the building and on the door.
Cadereyt has 11 suspects in custody.
The Secretary of National Defence has identified 11 individuals, including juveniles, who were members of a criminal group that operated primarily in the Cadereita area and is linked to kidnappings, murders, stalking and illegal burials.
According to the information released, during the first attempt on 11 November in the Los Alveros colony, eight people were detained and one detained person was released.
Three properties and a cell phone have been seized, confirming they're members of a criminal group called Los Zetas.
Another raid occurred at 6 a.m. on November 12th, when military personnel were patrolling the Rancho Viejo area of Cadereyta when they spotted two people in an unmarked car.
After the car was stopped, they did a search and found one rifle, a casing and 18 rounds.
Then, based on these statements, around 2pm on November 13th, one of the accomplices was arrested in the La Frauda area, and when he saw the soldiers, he tried to escape.
They were charged with illegal burials in General Terán, China and Cadereyta.
On Wednesday , the new Italian government will be appointed .
Prime Minister-elect Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce a new government that will face the crisis that is keeping this country above the precipice of economic disaster.
Prime Minister-elect Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce a new government that will face the crisis that is keeping the country above the brink of economic disaster and has put the entire eurozone in danger.
The presidential palace issued a statement announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to introduce a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with the political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult phase", the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that the obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well marked", he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, while Italy struggles to cope with a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt levels to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the tough austerity package demanded by European leaders, the only way to restore Italy's shattered credibility.
There's a lot of pressure on Monti to hurry, because of the volatility of the markets, the interest rates on Italian BTP bonds with a 10-year maturity have exceeded the 7 percent threshold, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for bailouts.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian employers' organization Confindustria, told reporters after meeting with Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government".
We believe that this government is the last chance to get Italy out of this burning situation.
Monti's hopes of success have been greatly increased by the support of the PDL party of Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday by the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to produce good results", Angelina Alfano, the secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the government with a technocratic majority, which is composed of Monti.
Support for the Parliament
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to push through unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in this effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure, warning that Monti's failure could spell disaster.
Monti opened talks on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women's organisations.
The round of talks will end Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitan, which allowed a very rapid process in response to the crisis.
After a brief fall at the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian bond yields have returned to the critical level, reacting to uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will succeed.
The rescue of Italy, whose public debt is €1.8 trillion, would be beyond the scope of the current euro area financial reserves.
Monti has stated that his government should remain in power until the next elections scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that he says politicians will only give him time to implement reforms and then call early elections.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that this government must be composed only of experts to lift Italy out of the trouble the country has been in due to financial pressure.
Political sources said that the bilateral mistrust and disagreement between the parties complicates the attempt to integrate political figures into the government.
