The quintet has included the country in their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary
"The trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to play one of the best shows in the nation next Sunday at the National Stadium.
We've been waiting for over 20 years, but the band themselves assures us that for them, the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
So said bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil.
The band is on a tour of South America to celebrate its 20th anniversary and will make a one-off stopover in Central America on Sunday the 20th.
He's performing at the National Stadium from 7:30 p.m. tonight with the angel band The X and the national musicians of Las Robertas.
This is a sample of the interview, the full transcript of which can be found on the website of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, it's a dream come true, Pearl Jam is playing in Costa Rica, do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
The Costa Rica trip is also our dream come true.
We've only been to South and Central America twice, and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation, it's a beautiful country, and I hope we can stay here for a few days.
So we're very excited to bring our music to you.
I'm asking because they literally love the band here, and the fans are having these days of preparation very intense.
What do you say to your most rocky supporters?
Thank you for standing by us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, and we thank you for waiting so long, and we're sorry it took us so long.
Some people are already talking about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that put you under more pressure?
Some of the greatest shows we've done in the last 21 years have come within weeks of each other.
We've done some great shows in Sao Paulo, and we're hoping that it'll get us in shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to the concert.
We love this country, we love surfing, we love the jungle, and for both of those things, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you know Costa Rica and its waves were suitable for surfing?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo, and the waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico, and those are the best places to surf, and that's how we learned about Costa Rica from people who love surfing.
Looking at your tour, you've put on a great show with a lot of songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, there's no limit to what we can do.
We're gonna try to put on the best show we can with the most diverse music, and we're gonna try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think part of it is because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs we're going to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven't played in a long time, we focus on them and we're also surprised, because we remember why we liked them so much and that we might have forgotten about them.
That's why the show is more interesting to us, and I think it's more interesting to people.
This tour is to celebrate 20 years of your artistic career.
Looking back, it's hard to believe all you've accomplished?
Yes, I'm sure you are.
First of all, I don't think either of us could have imagined that we'd be in one big rock band and that we'd be in it for over 20 years.
We realize how much power we've been given and it's touching that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We're lucky to be able to see the places we've always wanted to see.
We couldn't have done it better.
What did it mean to you to be a major part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It's always been an honor to be part of this group, where the greats are all represented.
The people at Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It's surprising that when a movement starts from a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
From time to time a group will form in a city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to appear from one city at a time.
We're proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them sometimes.
Last year, we were at the Alice in Chains festival, and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, and we saw Soundgarden on tour, and we're lucky that they're all our friends, and we're honored to be able to be part of this movement that started in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stick together and have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a lot longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think that first, we're all lucky to still be in this world, and second, it's the fact that we're always interested in each other.
We're all close friends, and that's how we've been able to open up musical avenues that leave everyone with enough freedom to experiment on their own.
We trust each other, we respect each other's music, and I think it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy, but thanks to your success, you can do whatever you want.
How do you find the balance?
As we grew older, it became easier and easier to find balance.
We try not to go on tour too much, because it's very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people come for music, you remember that you have to respect music and what you've given it, you can't get carried away by being famous, rock stars, which none of us ever really cared about.
What do you remember about the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs and it was something great at the beginning.
We'd been around as a band for three years and we never released an album until after Andy [Andrew Woods] died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long, and the most important thing is that we're still friends with Bruce and Greg, who started with us in the band, and when I listen to a song or look at a picture, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how I laughed with him, and it was always a pleasure to work with him, to laugh with him, to talk about music or football and so on.
She was an incredible person and we miss her so much.
The National Band of Las Robertas will be commissioned to open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as your forerunners?
Yes, the production company sent us videos with some designs, and this group was the one we liked the most, so we're curious what Las Robertas are going to offer live, and they have to be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words to Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Eddie, so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he adds the first thing he thinks.
Who influences you as a bass player?
A lot of people.
The first people I'm attacked by are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many I could talk all night about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam keep grunge going when it's not in fashion anymore?
I think we've all always felt slightly detached from the word grunge.
When I say grunge, I think of bands that I've mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and all the other bands that came out around the same time, and if the music is still that good, it's great because it's music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever before.
Your music was a little gloomy at first, but now it's more positive.
What is behind this change?
That's interesting because I feel like there are a few songs on the new album that are a little bit more light-hearted, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very gloomy, although they can sound positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them to me, I cried, and they're deeply dark songs.
I think that when you grow up and you have some trauma in your life, you lose a family member or a friend, these things start to affect your art and your music, and these two songs are just that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
Peru:
Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized Tuesday at a state hospital for tests of muscle loss in his lower limbs, his attending physician said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year sentence for human rights abuses committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has undergone four surgeries and is currently under medical supervision.
MP Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Canal N television station that Fujimori will undergo tests in three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases, where they should find out why he is in pain and why he is losing strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said that in his opinion Fujimori could be pardoned on humanitarian grounds, however the former president himself does not wish to be pardoned because he feels innocent.
He had four operations for tongue cancer, lost 60 pounds [18 kg], and was beset by other ailments, including severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in his pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and circulatory problems in his legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by an army killing squad operating illegally in the early years of his rule.
Mujica on a visit to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday, aiming to expand trade between the two nations and to touch on political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, on Wednesday, the most important meeting of a large-scale visit, including meetings with politicians, business leaders and representatives of the Uruguayan community living in Mexico, the program was released by the Uruguayan presidential office.
The meeting of the two presidents in Guadalajara will serve to exchange information on political issues between the two countries", the Uruguayan presidential office said on its website.
According to local media reports, Mujica will try to get Calderón to back Uruguay in a dispute with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a tax haven list at the G20 summit in Cannes, France.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude countries that continued to maintain their tax havens from the international community, a statement that prompted a negative opinion from Uruguay and consultation with the European country's ambassador.
Mexico has been the G20's president since November, a group of the world's most powerful developing and developed countries that have signed an information-sharing agreement with the Latin American country since January to prevent double taxation.
The Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) was signed on 15 March and entered into force on 1 January.
In trade terms, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) since 2004, which has increased trade in goods between the two countries.
The bearded plumber is running in 3D thanks to "Super Mario 3D Land".
For over 25 years, Super Mario has fought tirelessly to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the villain Bowser, but has never appeared in 3D: in "Super Mario 3D Land", he will fight for the love of a girl with stereoscopic technology.
The title, which is coming to stores around the world this month, was designed from the ground up to take advantage of all the features of the Nintendo 3DS handheld console, which allows you to play 3D games without the need for glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to tell you how to do stereoscopy without glasses", said Nintendo's Spanish press officer Omar Álvarez during a presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game created specifically for this medium", because up until this point successful films like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
A Nintendo spokesperson stated that in addition to being 3D, Super Mario 3D Land is an "available" video game that allows for fast and smooth gameplay.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple", whose task is to attract less skilled users.
Once you've passed this level, you can proceed to "round two" on levels of the game that are more challenging this time.
In addition, users can choose real-time between "aggressive D" or similar, which only affects the depth of the action, but will need to play in 3D to overcome various challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This new entry in Super Maria 3D also involves the return of the character to a portable console, which has not happened since 2005.
In this video game, Nintendo plays to the notes of the audience, repeating the successful formula of the previous games, in which the bearded man's plumber must go through dangerous mined platforms to free Princess Peach.
Although the player finds new moves, surroundings, disguises and enemies, the "playful" Luigi also appears.
Colom has approved the extradition of Portillo to the United States.
President Álvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he has taken steps to extradite former President Alfonso Portillo, who is to be held in the United States for conspiracy to launder US$70 million.
This ends a process that was intended to get Guatemala to respond to a request from a northern country that was demanding Portillo's extradition so that it could prosecute him.
At the press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was in line with the independence of the judiciary and the executive and that he recalled that the extradition had already been ordered by the criminal court.
He assured that during his tenure he had "not interfered" with court decisions and authorised all issues that came to his table.
In addition to Portilla, we're going to extradite Sergio Ruano Marroquin for murder and grievous bodily harm and Edgar Estrada Morales and Victor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Coloma's move is a step of execution after all the judicial and constitutional bodies have been exhausted to prosecute the former president who ruled from 2000 to 2004.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Tribunal and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo will be extradited after his legal situation in Guatemala is resolved and human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was found not guilty of embezzling $120 million from the Department of Defense during his presidency, a process that preceded the release, but the Attorney General appealed, putting the case back in play.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people in distress
The organization was created to help children without education not to feel marginalized.
The record of the first 25 years of the existence of the Trinijove social support organisation is very important: 6,000 young people who were threatened with social exclusion were helped.
This is in addition to the hundreds of jobs that have been created for this social group.
Yesterday's anniversary also served to present the balance sheets in a ceremony held in the former Fabra i Coats factory premises, attended by more than 300 people.
The Trinijove organisation was set up in the Trinitat Vella district in 1986 to help young people with low education, unemployment, drug addiction or in a situation where they could be socially excluded.
Yesterday's meeting in Sant Andreu was attended by a large number of representatives of organisations and institutions which have worked with the association over the past 25 years.
The diverse political representation, at the time of the elections, showed the unified nature of the work carried out by Triniyev.
Along with the President of the Generalitat, Artur Maas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujo, the ceremony was attended by the former Socialist Education Councillor, Ernest Maragall, and the former Deputy Mayor and current Ecological Socialist Councillor, Ricard Goma.
The present Adviser for Social Welfare and the Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of Social Work at La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa, also arrived in the Fabra i Coats Hall.
Mas said that Trinijove was founded in a very difficult time and that the present time also encounters a number of obstacles, but he added that the work the association has brought to date "is a good foundation".
The President cited Triniov as an example of how to fight against adverse circumstances and how to give courage to people in difficult situations.
"The crisis is nothing new for this organization and the work it does", he said.
The house was evacuated, where huge parties were held.
Intruders have taken 11 of the 13 apartments in the building at 51 Balmes.
12 occupants left the house yesterday at noon without resistance
All indications are that the nightmare that the neighbors of 51 Balmes Street were living through is finally over.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building at noon yesterday, where they were staying illegally and where they were hosting a giant party that the neighbors were building, by court order and without the intervention of the police.
After the operation, the door lock was replaced to prevent a repeat of the situation.
"From now on, the entrance will be guarded", declared the warden.
The occupants, who took 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest are occupied - took away all electrical and partial water equipment, painted the walls, and left behind all kinds of waste, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
The first three apartments were the site of huge parties that lasted up to two days and woke up the other tenants.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which was also damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that during the time the building was occupied, sales fell by 80%.
The owner of the discotheque points out that the occupants of the building were unfair competition to her because they sold drinks for 3 euros, whereas the disco costs 10.
The owner of the entertainment business also had to respond to complaints from neighbors about noise, but the problem was not with the disco patrons, but with the occupants of the house and especially those who attended the parties, which have increased in frequency and intensity in recent weeks, according to angry residents.
The owner of the disco explained that the problems were so great that they even made a deal with the building's owner, who has been removing her rent for nine months.
The city police also confirmed that they have received several complaints from neighbors over the situation in recent weeks.
The chairman of the city's PP group in the city hall, Alberto Fernández Díaz, last week demanded that "the building be evacuated immediately, thus ending the problems of civic coexistence that the neighbors are suffering and the destruction of the area".
The chairman of the People's Party explained that only one floor was taken last summer, but in recent months the occupants have been able to get into all floors of the building and almost all apartments, and in one of them there was even a theft.
In this regard, he added that "it is necessary to end impunity and to be consistent when it comes to acts against civic responsibility that have occurred in the building".
Yesterday, the city police also evacuated the building in Nou Barris.
At 3:30 p.m., police arrived at building 35 on Mont-Ral Street after being called by neighbors who saw four people entering the building.
All four were immediately arrested.
Park or mountains?
The architects have come together to write a lawsuit that involves more than just a controversy over fees.
The city's 16-door competition reopens the debate on the role of Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the boom of the now defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), the municipality published several pamphlets in support of Collserola Park.
The flyer defined the mountain as a large park in metropolitan Barcelona.
What's more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York's Central Park.
After the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper boundary of Barcelona, one of the few cities in Catalonia that is not oriented on a north-south axis but up (up) - down (down) (sea).
The qualification of Collserol as a nature reserve is in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with the wild boars instead of Yogi Bear.
That was the position until September, when the city council announced a mega-competition of 16 bids for the same number of entrance gates to Collserola.
Of course, the gate records more of the park's idea.
Either that, or someone's trying to put a gate on the field.
So the only question is, Collserola, park or mountain?
During the competition, both from a purely organisational point of view and on the basis of reflection on the city, this question becomes a central theme for all Barcelona architects.
It's as much a subject as when two members of this ancient caste of chosen people join hands in an elevator.
And it was this feat that brought about one of the rare coincidences between what the three Barcelona architects thought and the previous university professors.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the selection procedure has its reasons.
According to Roldan, after the Gulf side question was raised, the "mountain side" also "needs" to be discussed, so the speech by Ildefonso Cerdo on the green apples was not finished.
"We must start from the principle that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, it's very accessible.
Collserola is more complex", said the architect, for whom the name "Gates to Collserola" carries a "lexicological trap": we must not think of them "as entrances to the park, but rather as the definition of zones where it is possible to act".
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona, with experience in the world of urban planning, qualifies the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "certain dangers".
The danger stems from the "uncertainty of the public space project today" after the experience of the 1980s, which had its swan song in the Forum area.
The first concern is the very definition of where to build.
"To define something is to take the next step", that is, to move one step further.
"It is necessary to keep in mind the new urban planning tools, because the current ones (referring to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause a real disaster".
If we look more closely at the question, Modol considers that the Collserola valley slope can be "considered a park", but the Barcelona part cannot, for purely topographical reasons.
Modol also recalled that there is already work being done by Patronat de Collserola which "must not end up in the garbage dump", although he welcomed the fact that the City Council offers his committee to intervene in the project from the "first moment".
And furthermore, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is a sort of pass that allows architects to engage in the debate, but he "doubts" that it should be this very technical profile that leads to multidisciplinary teams ("it's all about skills", he adds) that need to be created: "Architects should be just tools".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the game its name is complex, because the selection criteria lack Collserole's global vision: "There have been 16 competitions that cover all the mountain-sea axis, but there is no longitudinal study that looks at the area and understands it as a whole".
That makes him, at least, a candidate for all 16 contests.
Otherwise, the design of one gate may conflict with the concept and definition of the architect of the neighbouring gate.
In his view, the City should ensure that the strip immediately above the Ronda de Dalt provides facilities throughout the zone to ensure a smooth transition between the city and the greenery.
The casino has pardoned Jonas Larrazabaal, who will be released
After 72 days of detention, the legal representative of Cadino Red granted clemency to the brother of the mayor of Monterrey in a trial in which he was prosecuted for alleged extortion.
Manuel Jonas Larrazábal has spent 72 days in prison and will now be released after being granted clemency by the legal representative of Casino Red before the Second Criminal Court of the same district, which was hearing a blackmail case against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the Casino Royale attack, the owner of the Casino Red, Sergio Gil García, published a series of photos and videos in which Manuel Jonás was supposed to ask him to pay an economic quota to the city of Monterrey to allow the illegal operation of the gambling house.
