According to Official Record 197/2011, Jonas Larrazabaal is granted a legal pardon, no appeal can be lodged in the proceedings against him, no claim for damages or punishment can be made.
After a hearing with the legal representative at about 3:50 p.m., the court ordered the immediate release of Larrazabel Breton.
The court clerk, Jorge Yanéz, arrived at the prison in the city of San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonas that he had been granted a formal pardon and that his case had been put on hold.
He also informed him that the judge had issued an immediate order for his release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome presented details of the plane crash that killed the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven other people.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) has informed that the results of the investigation into the accident that killed Prime Minister Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people show that the helicopter hit the ground at full power without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, said that before the plane took off, the pilot stated that the weather conditions allowed the flight.
"The parts that appear suggest that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, wings entangled in the branches of trees 25 meters from the place where the unit lost the hull".
He also informed that the unit was intended for 19 persons and therefore met all requirements for the transport of personnel.
Furthermore, he stated that based on the investigation carried out in the impact area, no components were found on the ground.
"The search revealed that the parts of the plane were not located anywhere else, so the plane hit the mainland intact.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, met all requirements for the transport of people.
The terrain is sloping from seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at this time, the most important thing is to get results as soon as possible, although the investigation could take several months or up to a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, stated that at the time of the crash, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was traveling at cruise speed and the accident occurred on soft ascent terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that at the time of the accident this was a routine overflight operation", he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jácome identified six key points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was operated in accordance with visual flight rules, i.e. the crew must be able to see the ground during the flight.
Weather conditions:
Reports from the AICM indicate adequate conditions at take-off, according to which the aircraft is heading towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Routes selected:
It is likely that the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility as far as the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Location of impact.
The collision coordinates and the last radar record of the helicopter match, it's likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of the flight path before the collision.
Dispersal of aircraft debris in restricted areas:
The information we have at present allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
The scattered plane debris diagram indicates that the helicopter was intact at the time of impact.
No fire or explosion was recorded.
There was no evidence of an explosion or fire at the scene.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During fieldwork, the remains of the plane were found at an altitude of up to 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain is sloping, the height of the slope ranges from seven to 30 degrees.
The photographs show footage of what is likely to have been a breakdown along the route.
The information provides elements that seem to suggest that the helicopter may have made contact with the ground at several locations.
After a thorough search of the accident area, which is larger than the designated area, no remains of the helicopter were found, reinforcing the assumption that the collision occurred when the helicopter was still intact.
The Mexican Health Insurance Institute has begun research on the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for childhood and adolescent obesity.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to identify the gene that causes obesity in children and adolescents.
In a report, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Center of the 21st Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists, and social workers had been set up.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, with or without permission, can also participate in the research, and people can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in the Valle de México, where they will be tested every Sunday from 8 a.m. onwards.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexico State) and since October 8 this activity is also being carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (Eastern Mexico State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children have been collected, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Centre (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the goal of this study was to identify the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people, thus preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people aged between six and 14, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that every Saturday, anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels, and genes (to identify genes involved in childhood obesity) are taken of all participants.
Cruz López said that the research reflects the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in childhood weight.
"Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, obesity increased by 77% in boys and 47% in girls, and there was a dramatic increase in overweight", said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one of the reasons for looking for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Native American genetic makeup, 30% European, and 5% African, reflected in the genes responsible for diabetes and obesity.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as the inability to burn off the excess energy we consume (calories) that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the participants was that they received an overall assessment of the children's condition, which would determine whether they were known to be overweight or obese.
He stated that even the presence of dark wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that an individual will suffer from metabolic problems and prediabetes.
The information is confidential for now, and doctors give it to the parents in writing, explaining all the measures and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent their children from getting sick.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the television all day, and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
Obesity is also caused by high caloric intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content, and genetic burden, which is the subject of this research.
There will be no spillways in the Asphalt of UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM School of Chemistry, creates modified asphalt with polymers, creating a mixture that has better functionality, regardless of climate and temperature
If the paving were properly maintained, nearly 200,000 excreta would not need to be repaired after each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, noted Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, adding that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, excreta would be significantly reduced or even eliminated.
In his talk on the technological causes of leaks given during the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that a laboratory under his direction was developing modified asphalt with polymers, which would produce a mixture having similar characteristics to asphalt but with greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, improving functionality and reducing the formation of sloughs.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a group of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight molecules called asphaltene, and low molecular weight molecules called maltene, which together give asphalt its typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost solid, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the strength of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperature, noted a chemical engineering expert.
A scientist at the School of Chemistry observed that most streets in Mexico City are covered with flexible paving, made up of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the topmost layers is an asphalt slab, made up of small stones that are poured into the asphalt and then pressed.
He emphasized that each stone that forms the insert is covered with asphalt.
When cars pass or when pressure is created, it is possible for the forces in the pavement to be well distributed.
If it were modified asphalt, they would decompose even better, a chemical engineer believes.
He added that the last layer of asphalt, called the mantle, is made of fine stone, sand, also poured into the asphalt.
As this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have a higher mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must provide for the friction of the road surface.
Since the cladding will be subject to heavy loads, the coat must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken with the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to be taken into account.
Once the terrain is wet, water spreads inwards and is difficult to get out, softening all the layers of the pavement and creating sloughs.
He explained that the first thing that happens during the process of making the slurry is that the film of the coat is damaged and then the asphalt is damaged, but it is not done all at once, but is a slow process that should be stopped at the first marks with proper maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of slurries, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of pavement must correspond to the load of vehicles and must be ensured that this load is not exceeded.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there is still a lot of work to be done on asphalt and that research is still in its infancy, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and allow the repair of landfills without the need to use high temperatures.
What did the Valle candidate lack to become the next Miss Colombia?
Analysis of the factors that contributed to Melina Ramírez Serna's failure to win the Miss Colombia crown.
Valle wins his 14th title in his first multi-miss.
Valle del Cauca has once again failed to win the Miss Colombia crown.
Melina Ramírez Serna had to be content with being on the winning podium, winning the silver crown and the sherpa, which made her the new first Miss Colombia.
