The Golden Rule on Balanced Budgeting
The Social Democrats and Christian Democrats, the ruling grand coalition government in Austria, decided on Tuesday to insert a "golden rule" of fiscal policy into the constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and avoid a case of Austria being downgraded by the rating agencies (AAA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the end of the ministerial meeting, at a time when Austria's public debt, at 74.6%, is well above the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but much lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency were reduced by just one degree from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more in interest every year", argued Chancellor and Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger, a Christian Democrat.
Austria thus follows up on the request of the Euro Area Summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where the Heads of State or Government strongly requested that the reduction of the public deficit and the achievement of the balance of the public accounts be enshrined in the Constitution or the Law of the same value by the end of 2012.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian Government is close to the 'German model', Germany being the first European country to adopt such a 'rule'.
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to be reduced by 0,75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, from 2017, the public structural deficit of the federal state will not be allowed to exceed 0,35% of GDP each year, while the Länder, as well as the municipalities, will have to report balanced budgets.
The objective is to bring public debt under the 60% criterion set out in the Maastricht Treaty by the 2020/21 horizon.
