Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogma
If there is one subject that cannot be grasped on the basis of short-term balances or under the emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of undertakings.
It is natural that the election meeting should be an opportunity to think about such inputs and about the place that takes energy from the core.
The debate will only be successful if all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options are explored.
France must base its position on objective facts and rational data.
There are seven billion people on the planet right now, but demographic change will double the demand for electricity between now and 2050 unless we deprive a significant portion of the world's population of essential life components.
At the same time, the shortage of fossil fuels will be needed to continue producing electricity, while not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that is currently missing from environmental debates.
The Fukushima accident has no effect on any of these parameters.
And that is why Germany remains alone in its decision to reject nuclear energy.
This is not the case in Belgium, which subordinates its decision to the need to find another source capable of replacing itself, nor in Switzerland, which considers it correct to build only last-generation power stations.
On the contrary, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, are continuing their projects with determination.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its fleet by one unit by rebuilding one power plant that had been interrupted by the Three Mile Island power plant disaster.
If the German renewable energy model is sometimes presented as an example, the reality is the opposite.
The choice of Berlin will be reflected in the rise in electricity prices, the increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, the sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal-fired power plants.
We'll feel all these unpleasant effects within a few months.
The case of Denmark is worth considering.
The European champion in wind power, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest consumers of coal and gas due to wind irregularities, which means that its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are 65% and 50% higher than the European average, respectively.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours will pay 40% more for electricity than the average French household.
While in a globalised economy energy costs are a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of keeping industry on the national territory, French companies enjoy the benefits of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would trigger a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make the beautiful claims of re-industrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power illusory.
A price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay, just as they are fundamentally not opposed to this energy, as opinion polls show.
Recall that the energy policy of our country has allowed to build a sector with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 secondary jobs.
The strong exporting sector draws large numbers of small and medium-sized specialised enterprises into international markets, creating jobs that cannot be transferred abroad.
If France were to decide to leave nuclear, it would sacrifice a large number of these SMEs and would lose EUR 6 billion a year, which the country receives from the export of nuclear equipment and services.
What power plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to run for 60 years while the manufacturer was scheduled to go bankrupt?
When solving the energy equation, we have to admit that there is no magic source for energy production, and there is no evil one.
The development of low-CO2 installations, nuclear installations and installations using renewable energy sources by the French industrial group AREVA demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is absolutely necessary to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have the National Office for Nuclear Safety, which carries out uncompromising and transparent supervision of existing nuclear power plants as well as the construction of the new plant in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, have the idea of safety in their blood.
In 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
The only one in Three Mile Island occurred in normal operating conditions and left no human casualties or environmental consequences.
The tragedy at Chernobyl was caused by the reactor's conception and inexcusable human error.
In the case of Fukushima, some seem to forget that the crash was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented proportions, killing tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident just as it did from the two before it.
The result of this step and the cooperation between the French and German nuclear safety authorities, operators and designers is that the EPR reactor represents a concept capable of withstanding such phenomena.
While all interested parties wishing to build a nuclear power plant are considering it, the halt of its construction in Flamanville would be an excellent gift to the competitors of the AREVA group and EDF and a clear path to their taking the lead in nuclear development.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy solutions for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogma and machinations to dominate a debate so crucial to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy of Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - the overwhelming police, courts and administration subjected to a policy of numbers, the compatibility of this policy with the "land of human rights" status that France boasts.
Recently, it was the administrative harassment of foreign students that became a topical issue when the Minister of the Interior (see Libération of 23 May) declared that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and waitresses".
But so far, it has rarely been discussed from an economic perspective.
I have to say, there's a pretty broad agreement between the left and the right in this area.
On the right, Jacques Chirac set the tone in 1976 when he declared that "900,000 unemployed people should not be a problem in a country where there are 2 million migrant workers" and on the left, Michel Rocard, when he said in 1990 that France "cannot accept all the poverty in the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of an invasion of French territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by both right and left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity we're willing to give to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande limits himself to banality when he states that joint development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem may hold true in elections, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in their recently published work synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, p. 352), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration movements on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration is stunting growth and hurting employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that these people can replace French workers, especially those with lower skills, and create pressure to reduce their wages.
But experience shows that in reality, immigrants are far more complementary than substitutes for French workers by performing jobs in sectors with a shortage of workers.
The low level of qualified immigrants in sectors which do not attract French workers and the highest level of qualified immigrants in dynamic sectors where training is not enough to provide jobs.
Positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, this complementary relationship between the French and migrants means that the arrival of immigrants has a positive impact on the wages and employment of French workers.
Giovanni Peri thus calculated that a 1% increase in migration movements would lead to a long-term increase in real wages of between 0,6% and 0,9%.
And it doesn't take into account the fact that diversity brought by immigrants contributes to thought and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among US Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems in European countries, on average at 1% of the total budget.
The World Labour Organisation, for example, estimates that in Germany, one immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will bring a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of EUR 150000 to the public budget over his lifetime.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy expressed the wish to make up for the missing growth rate "with his teeth in the sand".
The teeth used to deter immigrants had the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a precious and also a very fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, because although it was invented in Athens two thousand years ago, it has experienced throughout the 20th century the tragedies of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the colonels in Greece.
Some people might have believed that for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to conduct elections and conduct them in the most direct way possible.
But we've known since Napoleon that it was the ease of thinking.
Universal suffrage, while a necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition and can become an 'instrument of oppression', as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, the organization of departments and the control of power, education, enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it has been so since the beginning of the crisis of politics and democracy.
The recognition of the mistake of the Greek yes-no referendum will be of twofold revelation in this respect: it will reveal the necessity of a great return to political power, but it will also reveal the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its inadequacy.
This ambivalence must be thought through in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of democratic fervor have shifted today and that many of the Republican fighters are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We can't get anything by demanding a series of national referendums, organized on the basis of need and disorganized.
A white woman exposed to a European absolutist monarch or a bound leg jumping into the empty depths of nationalism: what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not want knives and guillotines, but a common, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we wouldn't even know where to stop counting anyway - because there is a crisis in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe, bowing to the dictates of the markets and the rating agencies, which suffers from its own incompetence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is being humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe which is slowly losing its sovereignty and with it each of its peoples.
There is an urgent need to return to the leadership of the European project of democratic sovereignty.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce their debt burden, get rid of market domination and invest for the future.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level which cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, otherwise we would be in disaster.
After a long struggle against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, they are all now calling for a European economic government.
Be that as it may.
But to think that without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such citizens, would be a new folly and a new dead end.
We must embark on a new phase of European construction.
To create a republic in France, it was necessary to "be" a republican.
A revolution in the interests was not enough.
This lesson continues.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a more politically democratic Europe and a truly European democratic sovereignty.
Let's become Europeans and build Europe.
