Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas to Europe
The long-distance Nord Stream pipeline, which connects Eastern Europe directly to Russia and runs along the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has started operating.
It must supply the equivalent of gas to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday's inauguration of the Nord Stream, a new undersea gas pipeline that will directly connect Russia and Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the control valve around to control the flow of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
The new pipeline will start to flow an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas to Western Europe each year via the first 1,224-kilometre pipeline linking the St. Petersburg region with the Mecklenburg-Pomerania Federal State.
The second pipeline, which must be completed by the end of 2012, will deliver a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to the entire French consumption.
And now there's the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction is a victory.
The project was strongly opposed by Poland and the Baltic states.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being piped through the country by any third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries are losing some of their power: the ability to pressure Russia by threatening to shut it off from Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw was the strongest in expressing this when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means to say that it's a politically sensitive issue.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained more confidence in its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, as the project has created rifts between Europeans from the East and West.
Russia only managed to implement its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, high-consumption Western states whose gas fields are coming to an end five years ago.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us", François Fillon confirmed at the opening ceremony of the pipeline, demonstrating at what point major gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom's senior executives present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a major technical achievement.
The submarine pipeline is made of steel and is reinforced with a concrete shell to protect it from the anchors of naval vessels.
It lies on the seabed at an average depth of 200 m.
It was built to avoid World War II-era minefields.
"For safety reasons, almost 100 of them had to be removed or destroyed", says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
The protection of fauna and flora also needed to be increased.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing 242 Eiffel bells, which is uninterrupted by valves or maintenance stations throughout its length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project's leaders turned it down when the Swedes were less than willing to see a Russian state-owned company permanently established off their shores.
"In the event of a malfunction, we can stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute", Jens Müller explains.
If the gas is not tight, the gas in the pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, since the welds were designed to produce a leak once every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline is checked from the outside by a submarine robot pulled by a ship, while the condition of the pipeline is checked from the inside by a device that circulates inside.
This one-meter diameter cigar-shaped device is inserted into the inside of the pipe and pressurized with gas.
At the destination, it shall provide accurate information on possible deformation of metal parts during the three days of travel at a speed of 3 m/s.
The long-distance pipeline was designed to run for 50 years without the slightest repair.
The circulation of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leading position remains with Gazprom, which holds a 51% stake.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15,5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased to this company, for a five-year renewable contract, all its gas transport capacity.
'Gazprom will profit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported,' Jens Müller explains.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was secured by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach EUR 7,4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, the investment costs thus increased to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be recovered, as the risk is borne solely by Gazprom.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea at Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
The valves are 15 feet high and form the gas exit gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of incoming gas before it is transported to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine - the brand notebook
The Italian company Moleskine, founded 50 years ago, wants to bring back the joy of writing.
It smells of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
Moleskin's notebook is easily recognizable by its black rectangular plates and its white-colored leaves, which seem to have aged over time.
After all, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born back in 1997.
At that time, the Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch a new, but distinctive, notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant working for the company, is in charge of launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old moleskin production technique, which is used, for example, to treat the surface of benches.
This type of notebook was highly prized by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought back an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand's head of design at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Sales rose by 26% between 2006 and 2010, to 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is far from the clandestine production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were made.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It's difficult to put together an artificial portrait of the buyer, because the notebook will appeal to businessmen as much as students or professionals.
The image of the Moleskin diary is that its owners are people of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded spirit.
A small Italian company that started with 12 employees has grown to almost 100 employees and, since 2008, has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributed his notebooks to bookstores and through the FNAC chain of shops to small boutiques in the heart of the city, where he was able to assert his identity.
"We followed the spirit of the times and this need for new writing, despite the tumultuous development of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskin's notebook: the brand recently opened the exhibition "Offering", where architects or artists exhibit their notebooks.
In August, she also unveiled a new notebook with a leopard image at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine profits from its success and this cultural aura and diversifies its products: bags, diaries, pencils, laptop cases ... The brand is expanding to a whole range of media.
A success that aroused envy: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by investment funds SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which wrote a new page in Moleskin's history.
Why is the proportion of unemployed handicapped workers so high?
Around 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
Today is the 15th week of employment for the disabled.
Despite the voluntary public policies introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate of disabled people is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Is that depressing?
"No", underlines Eric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, which organises the Week for Employment of Disabled People.
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high, but three times as high".
"However, much remains to be done".
It must be said that for unemployed disabled persons, numerous barriers to entry into employment remain.
These are older people: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They are low-skilled: 80% do not have a high school diploma and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work and which are "at the heart of the problem", according to Christiane Grapina, director-general of the Tremplin association, which was set up in 1992 to help enterprises recruit handicapped workers.
So much for objective brakes.
There are still unspoken ways of thinking that are certainly developing, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entrepreneurs pour la Cité found that managers surveyed had a 'low level of knowledge about disabled people' with' an exaggerated image of people in wheelchairs and psychological or mental deficiencies'.
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 Law.
The latest figures available, which date from 2008, show a figure of 2,6%.
"We are now moving around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the organisation charged with collecting fees from companies that do not comply with the law.
This is shown by the number of 'fined' enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to EUR 480 million).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on businesses", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large enterprises".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
